{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eda734c6-a139-4669-95e6-5e6d6707dc11","content":"The directory is empty — there's no project yet. No worries, here's exactly what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP stdio server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- These make it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata (required for nuget.org) -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server over stdio</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the package as a global/local dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users invoke (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish workflow\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server            # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimum. Optional but recommended: add `<PackageReadmeFile>`, `<PackageTags>`, and `<RepositoryUrl>` for better discoverability on nuget.org.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"66502e68-166c-40b7-a844-e86a4c925503","outputTokens":538},"id":"dd292947-f6f1-4879-9ac5-cdc4a4f1036c","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:48:56.957Z","parentId":"bbc22c6d-1e80-44bd-a64b-0a148c114360"}
